# RTK — Claude Code hook (profile: {{ .profile }})

Managed by chezmoi (WfOS). RTK ([Rust Token Killer](https://github.com/rtk-ai/rtk)) is the
recommended-default LLM output compressor: it proxies dev commands and rewrites their output to
cut tokens 60–90%. This file documents the **Claude Code hook** that the sibling
`settings.json.tmpl` renders. It mirrors `~/.factory/RTK.md` and is rendered **per profile**.

**This profile: RTK is {{ if $p.rtk }}ENABLED{{ else }}DISABLED{{ end }}.**
{{ if $p.rtk }}
The `PreToolUse` Bash hook rewrites commands transparently — e.g. `git status` → `rtk git status`
— with zero token overhead. You do not call `rtk` yourself for ordinary commands.
{{- else }}
No hook is rendered for this profile; commands run raw. Set `rtk = true` for this profile in
`.chezmoidata/profiles.toml` to enable it.
{{- end }}

## Meta commands (always run `rtk` directly — never rewritten)

```bash
rtk gain              # token-savings analytics
rtk gain --history    # command usage history with savings
rtk discover          # analyze history for missed opportunities
rtk proxy <cmd>       # run a raw command without filtering (debugging)
```

## Verify the install

```bash
rtk --version         # rtk X.Y.Z
rtk gain              # must work (not "command not found")
which rtk             # confirm the correct binary
```

⚠️ Name collision: if `rtk gain` fails, you may have `reachingforthejack/rtk` (Rust Type Kit)
installed instead of the token killer. The Dust shell layer (`config/shell/rtk.zsh`) guards on
exactly this (`rtk gain --help`) before routing anything.

## Swappability

RTK is wired from profile data, so opting out is a one-flag change (`rtk = false`) that drops the
hooks block from `settings.json`. The shell side (`config/shell/rtk.zsh`) stays a no-op unless rtk
is installed and `DUST_RTK=1`, so removing RTK never breaks a shell. INSTALL is owned by
`dust bootstrap` / the manifest `agent` module; this template owns only the per-profile wiring.

